General Assembly Raised Bill No. 5476
February Session, 2026 LCO No. 2703
Referred to Committee on GOVERNMENT OVERSIGHT
Introduced by:
(GOS)
AN ACT CONCERNING OVERSIGHT OF EFFORTS TO PREVENT
HUMAN TRAFFICKING.
Be it enacted by the Senate and House of Representatives in General
Assembly convened:
1 Section 1. (NEW) (Effective July 1, 2026) (a) There is established, within
2 the Office of Policy and Management, a Human Trafficking Prevention
3 Coordinator. The coordinator shall be appointed by the Secretary of the
4 Office of Policy and Management, and shall have experience with
5 working with victims of human trafficking. The coordinator shall
6 coordinate the efforts among executive branch state agencies and law
7 enforcement to prevent human trafficking in the state.
8 (b) The coordinator (1) shall conduct comprehensive planning on
9 efforts to combat human trafficking in the state and coordinate the
10 activities and programs of executive branch state agencies in prevention
11 efforts; (2) shall work in partnership with the Trafficking in Persons
12 Council, and other multidisciplinary partners to help align state-wide
13 prevention, identification and response activities; (3) may enter into
14 such contractual agreements, in accordance with established
15 procedures, as may be necessary for the discharge of the coordinator's
16 duties; and (4) unless otherwise provided by law, may receive any
LCO No. 2703 1 of 14

Raised Bill No. 5476
17 money, revenue or services from the federal government, corporations,
18 associations or individuals. All executive branch state agencies shall
19 provide any information or data needed by the coordinator to perform
20 the duties established under this section.
21 (c) The coordinator shall develop and implement a training
22 curriculum which may consist of recorded trainings, which can be
23 adapted for specific state agencies. Such training shall implement best
24 practices and include, but need not be limited to, (1) awareness and
25 compliance with the laws and protocols concerning trafficking of minor
26 children, (2) identification of, access to and provision of services for
27 victims of trafficking, (3) de-escalation and harm reduction techniques
28 when encountering victims of trafficking, and (4) techniques on
29 receiving disclosures of trauma from minor children and adults. The
30 coordinator may offer such training to state agencies, law enforcement
31 agencies, health care facilities, human services agencies, school
32 personnel and nonprofit organizations.
33 (d) The coordinator shall create a database for state agencies to report
34 incidents of human trafficking in the state. Such database shall protect
35 the personal information of any victims of human trafficking and such
36 information shall not be disclosed under the Freedom of Information
37 Act, as defined in section 1-200 of the general statutes.
38 (e) The coordinator shall develop and maintain a state-wide
39 directory, organized by region, that identifies providers of services for
40 victims of human trafficking. The coordinator shall evaluate the
41 availability of such services and identify any gaps in funding or
42 geographic regions where services are lacking.
43 (f) Not later than January 1, 2027, and annually thereafter, the
44 coordinator shall submit a report, in accordance with the provisions of
45 section 11-4a of the general statutes, to the joint standing committees of
46 the General Assembly having cognizance of matters relating to
47 government oversight, the judiciary and appropriations and the
LCO No. 2703 2 of 14

Raised Bill No. 5476
48 budgets of state agencies. Such report shall include, but need not be
49 limited to, the activities of the coordinator during the prior year, any
50 recommendations and any recommendations for legislation to
51 implement the coordinator's recommendations.
52 Sec. 2. Subsections (a) and (b) of section 46a-170 of the 2026
53 supplement to the general statutes are repealed and the following is
54 substituted in lieu thereof (Effective July 1, 2026):
55 (a) There is established a Trafficking in Persons Council that shall be
56 within the Commission on Women, Children, Seniors, Equity and
57 Opportunity for administrative purposes only.
58 (b) The council shall consist of the following members: (1) The Chief
59 State's Attorney, or a designee; (2) the Chief Public Defender, or a
60 designee; (3) the Commissioner of Emergency Services and Public
61 Protection, or the commissioner's designee; (4) the Labor Commissioner,
62 or the commissioner's designee; (5) the Commissioner of Social Services,
63 or the commissioner's designee; (6) the Commissioner of Public Health,
64 or the commissioner's designee; (7) the Commissioner of Mental Health
65 and Addiction Services, or the commissioner's designee; (8) the
66 Commissioner of Children and Families, or the commissioner's
67 designee; (9) the Commissioner of Consumer Protection, or the
68 commissioner's designee; (10) the Commissioner of Developmental
69 Services, or the commissioner's designee; (11) the Commissioner of
70 Transportation, or the commissioner's designee; (12) the director of the
71 Basic Training Division of the Police Officer Standards and Training
72 Council, or the director's designee; (13) the Child Advocate, or the Child
73 Advocate's designee; (14) the Victim Advocate, or the Victim Advocate's
74 designee; (15) a chairperson of the Commission on Women, Children,
75 Seniors, Equity and Opportunity, or the chairperson's designee; (16) the
76 Secretary of the State, or a designee; (17) the Human Trafficking
77 Prevention Coordinator; (18) one representative of the Office of Victim
78 Services of the Judicial Branch appointed by the Chief Court
79 Administrator; [(17)] (19) a municipal police chief appointed by the
