113 Sec. 3. Subsection (b) of section 17a-3 of the general statutes is
114 repealed and the following is substituted in lieu thereof (Effective October
115 1, 2026):
116 (b) The state-wide program of services shall provide services and
117 placements that are clinically indicated and appropriate to the needs of
118 each child or youth. In furtherance of this purpose, the department shall:
119 (1) Develop a comprehensive program for prevention and treatment of
120 problems experienced by children and youths and provide a flexible,
121 innovative and effective program for the placement, care and treatment
122 of children and youths committed by any court to the department,
123 transferred to the department by other departments, or voluntarily
124 admitted to the department; (2) provide appropriate services to the
125 families of children and youths as needed to achieve the purposes of
126 sections 17a-1 to 17a-26, inclusive, 17a-28 to 17a-49, inclusive, and 17a-
127 51; (3) establish incentive paid work programs for children and youths
128 under the care of the department and the rates to be paid such children
129 and youths for work done in such programs, and may provide
130 allowances to children and youths in the custody of the department; (4)
131 collect, interpret and publish statistics relating to children and youths
132 committed to the department; (5) conduct studies of any program,
133 service or facility developed, operated, contracted for, licensed or
134 supported by the department in order to evaluate its effectiveness; (6)
135 establish staff development and other training and educational
136 programs designed to improve the quality of departmental services and
137 programs, which shall include, but not be limited to, training in the
138 prevention, identification and effects of family violence and the training
139 on human trafficking developed under section 4 of this act, and may
140 establish educational or training programs for children, youths, parents
141 or other interested persons on any matter related to the promotion of
142 the well-being of children, including, but not limited to, the prevention
143 and treatment of mental illness, substance use disorders and other
144 disabilities in children and youths; (7) require each social worker trainee
145 to complete the training in the prevention, identification and effects of
LCO No. 2703 5 of 14

Raised Bill No. 5476
146 family violence established pursuant to subdivision (6) of this
147 subsection and on and after January 1, 2027, the training on human
148 trafficking developed under section 4 of this act, prior to being assigned
149 a case load; (8) develop and implement aftercare and follow-up services
150 appropriate to the needs of any child or youth under the care of the
151 department; (9) establish a case audit unit to monitor each regional
152 office's compliance with regulations and procedures; (10) develop and
153 maintain a database listing available community service programs
154 funded by the department; (11) provide outreach and assistance to
155 persons caring for children whose parents are unable to care for such
156 children by informing such persons of programs and benefits for which
157 they may be eligible; and (12) collect data sufficient to identify the
158 housing needs of children served by the department and share such data
159 with the Department of Housing.
160 Sec. 4. (NEW) (Effective from passage) (a) The Commissioner of
161 Children and Families shall, within available appropriations, develop
162 and provide training to all employees of the Department of Children
163 and Families and all providers that provide services pursuant to a
164 contract with the department, regarding the trafficking of minor
165 children. The training shall include, but need not be limited to, (1)
166 awareness and compliance with the laws and protocols concerning
167 trafficking of minor children, (2) identification of, access to and
168 provision of services for minor children who are victims of trafficking,
169 (3) de-escalation and harm reduction techniques when encountering
170 minor children who are victims of trafficking, and (4) techniques on
171 receiving disclosures of trauma from minor children. The commissioner
172 may use the training curriculum developed by the Human Trafficking
173 Prevention Coordinator pursuant to section 1 of this act to satisfy the
174 requirements of this section.
175 (b) Each employee of the department or contracted-with provider
176 shall complete the initial educational training program not later than
177 July 1, 2027, and shall complete the refresher training program every
178 three years thereafter, provided any such employee shall complete such
LCO No. 2703 6 of 14

Raised Bill No. 5476
179 initial educational training program not later than six months after
180 beginning such employment or July 1, 2027, whichever is later, or in the
181 case of a provider, not later than six months after entering into a contract
182 with the department or July 1, 2027, whichever is later.
183 Sec. 5. (NEW) (Effective October 1, 2026) (a) The Chief Court
184 Administrator shall, within available appropriations, develop and
185 provide training to all employees of the Court Support Services Division
186 within the Judicial Branch regarding the trafficking of minor children.
187 The training shall include, but need not be limited to, (1) awareness and
188 compliance with the laws and protocols concerning human trafficking,
189 (2) identification of, access to and provision of services for victims of
190 trafficking, (3) de-escalation and harm reduction techniques when
191 encountering victims of human trafficking, and (4) techniques on
192 receiving disclosures of trauma from minor children. The Chief Court
193 Administrator may use the training curriculum developed by the
194 Human Trafficking Prevention Coordinator pursuant to section 1 of this
195 act to satisfy the requirements of this section.
196 (b) Each employee of the division shall complete the initial
197 educational training program not later than July 1, 2027, and shall
198 complete the refresher training program every three years thereafter,
199 provided any such employee shall complete such initial educational
200 training program not later than six months after beginning such
201 employment or July 1, 2027, whichever is later.
202 Sec. 6. (Effective from passage) Not later than July 1, 2027, the
203 Commissioner of Children and Families, in conjunction with the
204 appropriate local law enforcement agency, shall assess the security of
205 the placement location, whether public or private, of any child who is
206 placed in out-of-home care by the Department of Children and Families
207 pursuant to an emergency order under subsection (e) of section 17a-101g
208 of the general statutes or an order of temporary custody or an order of
209 commitment under section 46b-129 of the general statutes, and
210 determine whether additional lighting, security cameras or other
LCO No. 2703 7 of 14

Raised Bill No. 5476
211 measures are needed to increase the security of such location. Not later
212 than August 1, 2027, the commissioner shall submit a report, in
213 accordance with the provisions of section 11-4a of the general statutes,
214 to the joint standing committees of the General Assembly having
215 cognizance of matters relating to children and government oversight.
216 Such report shall include the results of such assessment.
217 Sec. 7. Subsection (a) of section 46a-13l of the general statutes is
218 repealed and the following is substituted in lieu thereof (Effective July 1,
219 2026):
220 (a) The Child Advocate shall:
221 (1) Evaluate the delivery of services to children by state agencies and
222 those entities that provide services to children through funds provided
223 by the state;
224 (2) Review periodically the procedures established by any state
225 agency providing services to children to carry out the provisions of
226 sections 46a-13k to 46a-13p, inclusive, with a view toward the rights of
227 the children and recommend revisions to such procedures;
228 (3) Review complaints of persons concerning the actions of any state
229 or municipal agency providing services to children and of any entity
230 that provides services to children through funds provided by the state,
231 make appropriate referrals and investigate those where the Child
232 Advocate determines that a child or family may be in need of assistance
233 from the Child Advocate or that a systemic issue in the state's provision
234 of services to children is raised by the complaint;
235 (4) Pursuant to an investigation, provide assistance to a child or
236 family who the Child Advocate determines is in need of such assistance
237 including, but not limited to, advocating with an agency, provider or
238 others on behalf of the best interests of the child;
239 (5) Periodically review the facilities and procedures of any and all
LCO No. 2703 8 of 14

Raised Bill No. 5476
240 institutions or residences, public or private, where a juvenile has been
241 placed by any agency or department, including, but not limited to,
242 Specialized Trauma-Informed Treatment Assessment and Reunification
243 Enhancement Plan homes;
244 (6) Recommend changes in state policies concerning children
245 including changes in the system of providing juvenile justice, child care,
246 foster care and treatment;
247 (7) Take all possible action including, but not limited to, conducting
248 programs of public education, undertaking legislative advocacy and
249 making proposals for systemic reform and formal legal action, in order
250 to secure and ensure the legal, civil and special rights of children who
251 reside in this state;
252 (8) Provide training and technical assistance to attorneys
253 representing children and guardians ad litem appointed by the Superior
254 Court;
255 (9) Periodically review the number of special needs children in any
256 foster care or permanent care facility and recommend changes in the
257 policies and procedures for the placement of such children;
258 (10) Serve or designate a person to serve as a member of the child
259 fatality review panel established in subsection (b) of this section;
260 (11) Take appropriate steps to advise the public of the services of the
261 Office of the Child Advocate, the purpose of the office and procedures
262 to contact the office;
263 (12) Prepare an in-depth report on conditions of confinement,
264 including, but not limited to, compliance with section 46a-152,
265 regarding children twenty-one years of age or younger who are held in
266 secure detention or correctional confinement in any facility operated by
267 a state agency. Such report shall be submitted, in accordance with the
268 provisions of section 11-4a, to the joint standing committee of the
