284 Sec. 8. (Effective from passage) (a) There is established a temporary task
285 force to be known as the Human Trafficking Prevention and Response
286 Task Force, which shall (1) be made up of the existing membership of
287 the Statewide Steering Committee of the Regionalized Human
288 Trafficking Recovery Taskforce established by the Division of Criminal
289 Justice, including representation from relevant state agencies, law
290 enforcement, prosecutors, providers that specialize in providing
291 services to trafficking victims, child advocacy centers and
292 multidisciplinary teams, survivor-informed representatives and other
293 members appointed by the Regionalized Human Trafficking Recovery
294 Taskforce as necessary to carry out the purposes of this section, and (2)
295 serve as a public-private partnership to implement the
296 recommendations set forth in the Regionalized Human Trafficking
297 Recovery Taskforce's report entitled "A Blueprint to Strengthen
298 Connecticut's Response to Human Trafficking".
299 (b) Such implementation shall include, but need not be limited to:
LCO No. 2703 10 of 14

Raised Bill No. 5476
300 (1) Advancing development of a permanent state-wide governing
301 body to coordinate the state's anti-trafficking response across agencies
302 and service providers and to create state-wide standards related to such
303 coordination;
304 (2) Creating and implementing a standardized, cross-disciplinary
305 human trafficking training framework and centralized learning
306 management system;
307 (3) Developing and implementing a unified state-wide data collection
308 process based on shared definitions, standardized reporting fields and
309 secure data-sharing protocols;
310 (4) Designing and implementing standardized, trauma-informed
311 screening questions and referral pathways to ensure consistent
312 identification of and response to victims of human trafficking across
313 systems;
314 (5) Expanding and strengthening state-wide service capacity by
315 mapping and verifying existing providers, identifying service and
316 funding gaps and supporting development of a vetted state-wide
317 resource directory; and
318 (6) Reviewing trafficking trends, identifying systemic gaps and
319 developing policy recommendations to be submitted to the Trafficking
320 in Persons Council established pursuant to section 46a-170 of the
321 general statutes, as amended by this act, consistent with the work
322 undertaken pursuant to this subsection.
323 (c) The task force shall not replace or supersede the statutory
324 authority of Trafficking in Persons Council established pursuant to
325 section 46a-170 of the general statutes, as amended by this act.
326 (d) Not later than January 1, 2027, and annually thereafter until three
327 years after the effective date of this section or the submission of a final
328 report, whichever is later, the task force shall submit a report, in
LCO No. 2703 11 of 14

Raised Bill No. 5476
329 accordance with the provisions of section 11-4a of the general statutes,
330 to the joint standing committees of the General Assembly having
331 cognizance of matters relating to government oversight and the
332 judiciary. Such report shall include any activities of the task force during
333 the year preceding the report, and the final report shall detail the
334 proposed structure, authority and funding of the permanent state-wide
335 governing body described in subdivision (1) of subsection (b) of this
336 section. The task force shall terminate on the date that it submits such
337 final report.
338 Sec. 9. Subsection (b) of section 17a-106a of the general statutes is
339 repealed and the following is substituted in lieu thereof (Effective July 1,
340 2026):
341 (b) The Commissioner of Children and Families, as department head
342 of the lead agency, and the appropriate state's attorney [may] shall
343 establish multidisciplinary teams for the purposes of (1) reviewing
344 particular cases or particular types of cases, (2) coordinating the
345 intervention in and prevention of child abuse or neglect or trafficking of
346 children and the treatment of abused, neglected or trafficked children in
347 each judicial district, (3) reviewing selected cases of child abuse or
348 neglect or trafficking of children, (4) advancing and coordinating the
349 prompt investigation of suspected cases of child abuse or neglect or
350 trafficking of children, (5) reducing the trauma experienced by alleged
351 victims of such abuse or neglect or trafficking and, (6) ensuring the
352 treatment of abused, neglected or trafficked children and the protection
353 of such children and their families. The head of the local law
354 enforcement agency or such head's designee may request the assistance
355 of the Division of State Police within the Department of Emergency
356 Services and Public Protection in order to accomplish such purposes.
357 Sec. 10. Section 17a-106f of the general statutes is repealed and the
358 following is substituted in lieu thereof (Effective July 1, 2026):
359 (a) The Commissioner of Children and Families [may] shall: (1)
LCO No. 2703 12 of 14

Raised Bill No. 5476
360 Provide child welfare services for any minor child residing in the state
361 who is identified by the Department of Children and Families as a
362 victim of trafficking, as defined in section 46a-170, as amended by this
363 act; and (2) provide appropriate services to a minor child residing in the
364 state who the Department of Children and Families reasonably believes
365 may be a victim of trafficking in order to safeguard the welfare of such
366 minor child. For purposes of this section and section 17a-106a, as
367 amended by this act, "minor child" means any person under eighteen
368 years of age.
369 (b) The Commissioner of Children and Families [may] shall, within
370 available appropriations, provide training to law enforcement officials
371 regarding the trafficking of minor children. The training shall include,
372 but not be limited to, (1) awareness and compliance with the laws and
373 protocols concerning trafficking of minor children, (2) identification of,
374 access to and provision of services for minor children who are victims
375 of trafficking, and (3) any other services the department deems
376 necessary to carry out the provisions of this section and section 17a-106a,
377 as amended by this act.
This act shall take effect as follows and shall amend the following
sections:
Section 1 July 1, 2026 New section
Sec. 2 July 1, 2026 46a-170(a) and (b)
Sec. 3 October 1, 2026 17a-3(b)
Sec. 4 from passage New section
Sec. 5 October 1, 2026 New section
Sec. 6 from passage New section
Sec. 7 July 1, 2026 46a-13l(a)
Sec. 8 from passage New section
Sec. 9 July 1, 2026 17a-106a(b)
Sec. 10 July 1, 2026 17a-106f
Statement of Purpose:
To establish a Human Trafficking Prevention Coordinator, add
additional members to the Trafficking in Persons Council, require all
LCO No. 2703 13 of 14

Raised Bill No. 5476
employees of the Department of Children and Families and the Court
Support Services Division to undergo training regarding human
trafficking, require the Commissioner of Children and Families to assess
the security of placement locations, require the Child Advocate to
submit an annual report, establish a temporary task force and make
various duties of the Department of Children and Families concerning
trafficking mandatory.
